  "prompt": "Define melting point and boiling point? What is the difference?",
  "response": "Let me explain melting point and boiling point:\n\nMelting Point:\n- The temperature at which a solid substance changes from a solid to a liquid state\n- Occurs at a specific temperature under standard pressure\n- The substance remains at this temperature during the entire phase change\n- Represents the point where solid and liquid phases coexist in equilibrium\n\nBoiling Point:\n- The temperature at which a liquid substance changes from a liquid to a gas (vapor) state\n- Occurs at a specific temperature under standard pressure\n- The substance remains at this temperature during the entire phase change\n- Represents the point where liquid and gas phases coexist in equilibrium\n\nKey Differences:\n1. Phase change:\n- Melting point involves solid \u2192 liquid transition\n- Boiling point involves liquid \u2192 gas transition\n\n2. Energy required:\n- Melting point requires less energy compared to boiling point\n- Boiling point requires significantly more energy to break intermolecular bonds\n\n3. Temperature range:\n- Melting points are typically lower than boiling points\n- Boiling points are usually at much higher temperatures\n\nExample:\nWater: \n- Melting point = 0\u00b0C (32\u00b0F)\n- Boiling point = 100\u00b0C (212\u00b0F)",
